>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Lube and Condoms Compatibility Guide</h1>
      <p>Which lubes prevent breakage, and which ones destroy your protection.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <p>Using a personal lubricant with condoms is highly recommended. It increases pleasure, reduces discomfort, and significantly decreases the friction that causes condoms to break. However, pairing the wrong lube with the wrong condom material can destroy the condom in seconds, entirely compromising your protection against STIs and unintended pregnancy.</p>

      <p><em>This article is part of our comprehensive <a href="/sites/nookienook/lubricant-guide">Ultimate Guide to Personal Lubricants</a>.</em></p>

      <h2>The Compatibility Cheat Sheet</h2>
      <p>Here is the most important rule of thumb to remember:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Latex Condoms:</strong> Safe with Water and Silicone. <strong>DESTROYED by Oil.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Polyisoprene Condoms:</strong> Safe with Water and Silicone. <strong>DESTROYED by Oil.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Polyurethane Condoms:</strong> Safe with Water, Silicone, and Oil.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Danger of Oil-Based Lubes</h2>
      <p>Oil-based lubricants—including commercial oil lubes, Vaseline (petroleum jelly), baby oil, lotion, coconut oil, and massage oil—chemically react with natural rubber latex and synthetic polyisoprene. This reaction weakens the material instantly. A condom exposed to oil can tear or disintegrate within minutes. If you are using latex barriers, you must strictly avoid all oils. Learn more in our <a href="/sites/nookienook/oil-based-lube-guide">Oil-Based Lube Guide</a>.</p>

      <h2>Water-Based Lube: The Universal Choice</h2>
      <p><a href="/sites/nookienook/water-based-lube-guide">Water-based lubricants</a> are safe to use with absolutely every type of condom on the market. If you are ever unsure about condom compatibility, water-based is your safest bet.</p>

      <h2>Silicone Lube: Long-Lasting Protection</h2>
      <p><a href="/sites/nookienook/silicone-lube-guide">Silicone-based lubricants</a> are also universally safe with all condom materials. Because silicone doesn't dry out, it is an excellent choice for extended sessions, providing a long-lasting, friction-reducing barrier that helps keep the condom intact.</p>

      <h2>Pro-Tip: The "Drop in the Tip" Method</h2>
      <p>To maximize pleasure and minimize breakage, try putting a single drop of compatible (water or silicone) lube inside the tip of the condom before rolling it down the shaft. This increases sensitivity for the wearer and ensures there is no dry friction between the glans and the latex, which is a common cause of tearing.</p>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>Can I use Vaseline with condoms?</h3>
        <p>No. Vaseline (petroleum jelly) is oil-based and will rapidly degrade latex and polyisoprene condoms, causing them to break. It should never be used with these types of condoms.</p>

        <h3>What lube is safe for all condoms?</h3>
        <p>Both water-based and silicone-based lubricants are completely safe to use with all types of condoms, including latex, polyurethane, and polyisoprene.</p>

        <h3>Can lube stop a condom from breaking?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Applying a small drop of compatible water-based or silicone-based lube to the inside tip of the condom before rolling it on, and applying plenty to the outside, drastically reduces friction and the risk of tearing.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Return to the <a href="/sites/nookienook/lubricant-guide">Main Lubricant Guide</a> to compare safe lubricant options.</p>
    </div>
